ag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When someone says \"deploy to the server,\" it means we're referring to the hardware where the operating system and processors are. It means we're running our application, the one we've coded, on that machine. This hardware allows us to save something to the system and retrieve it. That‚Äôs what a server does. Deployment is all about saving and running our code on that hardware machine"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"can-we-use-our-systme-as-server"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Can we use our systme as server?"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The answer is yes, but the question is: will you be able to provide what a server from AWS offers? No, because you have limited RAM, limited memory, and no 24/7 access. So, while it's possible, it‚Äôs not practical. AWS and other servers run 24/7, have large-scale RAM and memory, and their processors are very powerful. Internet connection is also a concern."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"ip-address"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"IP Address"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A system can be identified by one address. For your computer, this address might change, but for servers, it does not. Servers have a dedicated IP address that never changes, which is why they are called servers. They are designed to serve, and they also have multiple hardware servers running in different locations. For example, when you create a Firebase server, it will ask where you want your server, such as Singapore. To create a real-time database server, you just click, and you‚Äôll be asked to choose the physical location where you want to connect."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"node-server"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Node Server"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What we do now and in the future is create servers that can handle requests from the outside world. That‚Äôs what Node.js is all about. Now, let‚Äôs discuss the architecture and dive deeper into it."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"client-sevrer-acrtictire"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Client Sevrer Acrtictire"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A client is simply a person or system trying to access your server. For example, if someone opens a browser on their laptop and tries to access a file, whenever a client hits a URL (e.g., "},{"type":"element","tag":"a","props":{"href":"http://www.heyashu.com/"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"www.heyashu.com"}]},{"type":"text","value":"), the browser (the client) wants to access files from Heyashu. A socket connection is opened, and there is something on the server side listening to these requests. An application deployed somewhere listens for these requests, and that machine or app is called the server. There might be multiple clients making similar requests to the server's assets. As we've seen with libuv and Node.js, the server handles these requests by receiving data through the socket connection and sending it back to the client. And that's the whole process."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"image.png","src":"https://heyashu.in/images/blogs/e11p2.png"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"tcp-ip-protocolweb"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"TCP IP Protocol/Web"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Whenever data is sent, it uses the "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Transfer Control Protocol (TCP)"}]},{"type":"text","value":". Again, this falls under the academic side of computer networking, so you can learn more about it by looking up "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"TCP/IP connections"}]},{"type":"text","value":" on the internet. Multiple computers are connected to each other using the internet, which is why it‚Äôs called the web, and each has an address. But what does \"protocol\" mean? It means rules. Communication must follow some rules, that‚Äôs all. For example, if I start writing these notes in Chinese, you wouldn‚Äôt understand. By the way, I‚Äôm writing digital notes on Node.js in "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Hinglish"}]},{"type":"text","value":" ‚Äî check here. So, rules are set, and that‚Äôs how communication works."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"other-protoals-24"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Other protoals 24"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"HTTP, FTP, SMTP are different types of request protocols. Depending on the type of request, different rules are used to transfer data. It's like getting things from a shop ‚Äî different items have different rules. For example, water needs a bottle, but vegetables need a packet. The same applies to requests in a server; the protocol defines the rules. For normal web requests, we use the "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"HTTP protocol"}]},{"type":"text","value":" (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"image.png","src":"https://heyashu.in/images/blogs/e11p3.png"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h3","props":{"id":"how-data-is-sent-to-the-client-data-transfer"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How data is sent to the client? Data Transfer"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Data is not sent in bulk; it is sent in chunks, which in computer network language are called "},{"type":"element","tag":"strong","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":